For this task, create an EC2 instance with following requirements:

1) The name of the instance must be devops-ec2.
2) You can use the Amazon Linux AMI to launch this instance.
3) The Instance type must be t2.micro.
4) Create a new RSA key pair named devops-kp.
5) Attach the default (available by default) security group.
Using the AWS Console:
1. Login to AWS Console:
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Log in with your credentials.
2. Navigate to EC2 Service:
In the search bar at the top, type EC2 and select EC2 from the list of services.
3. Launch a New EC2 Instance:
In the EC2 dashboard, click on Launch Instance.
4. Configure the Instance:
1. Choose an Amazon Machine Image (AMI):
  Select Amazon Linux 2 AMI (it is the default Amazon Linux AMI).
2. Choose an Instance Type:
  Select t2.micro (eligible for the free tier if your account qualifies).
3. Configure Instance Details:
  Keep the default settings, or configure as per your needs.
  Ensure Auto-assign Public IP is set to Enable if you want your instance to be accessible from the internet.
4. Add Storage:
  The default 8 GiB size should be sufficient, but adjust as needed.
5. Add Tags:
   Click Add Tag.
   Set the Key to Name and the Value to devops-ec2 to name your instance.
6. Configure Security Group:
  Choose the default security group (it is available by default).
7. Select Key Pair:
  Create a new key pair.
  Name the key pair devops-kp.
  Download the .pem file, which you will use to connect to your instance.
  Acknowledge that you have downloaded the key pair and proceed.
8.  Review and Launch:
  Review your settings and click Launch.
5. Instance Initialization:
Wait for your EC2 instance to be in the running state. You can see the status in the EC2 dashboard.

Using the AWS CLI:
1. Create a New RSA Key Pair:
First, create the RSA key pair named devops-kp. Run the following command:

aws ec2 create-key-pair --key-name devops-kp --query "KeyMaterial" --output text > devops-kp.pem

This command will create the key pair devops-kp and save the private key (devops-kp.pem) to your local machine. Make sure to keep it safe.

2. Launch the EC2 Instance:
Now, launch the EC2 instance with the specified requirements using the following command:
aws ec2 run-instances \
  --image-id ami-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx \  # Replace with the correct AMI ID for Amazon Linux 2
  --instance-type t2.micro \
  --key-name devops-kp \
  --security-group-ids sg-xxxxxxxx \  # The security group ID for the default security group (itâ€™s often automatically used)
  --tag-specifications 'ResourceType=instance,Tags=[{Key=Name,Value=devops-ec2}]' \
  --count 1 \
  --associate-public-ip-address

3. Verify the Instance:
To check if your instance was launched successfully, use the following command:
aws ec2 describe-instances --filters "Name=tag:Name,Values=devops-ec2"


